ex("Deque Operations","Use deque for efficient operations at both ends.","data_structures","deques",2,"from collections import deque\n\n# TODO: Show append/appendleft, pop/popleft, rotate\n","After appends: deque([0, 1, 2, 3, 4])\nAfter rotate(2): deque([3, 4, 0, 1, 2])\nPopleft: 3","deque supports O(1) operations at both ends.","from collections import deque\n\nd = deque([1, 2, 3])\nd.appendleft(0)\nd.append(4)\nprint(f'After appends: {d}')\nd.rotate(2)\nprint(f'After rotate(2): {d}')\nprint(f'Popleft: {d.popleft()}')","deque (double-ended queue) provides O(1) append/pop from both ends. rotate(n) moves n elements from the right end to the left. It's ideal for sliding windows and BFS.","SE: P6")
ex("Hash Map Implementation","Implement a basic hash map with get, set, and delete.","data_structures","hash_tables",5,"class HashMap:\n    # TODO: Implement with chaining for collision resolution\n    pass\n\nhm = HashMap(size=8)\nhm.put('name', 'Alice')\nhm.put('age', 25)\nhm.put('city', 'Sydney')\nprint(hm.get('name'))\nprint(hm.get('age'))\nhm.delete('age')\nprint(hm.get('age'))","Alice\n25\nNone","Use hash() % size for bucket index, lists for chaining.","class HashMap:\n    def __init__(self, size=8):\n        self.size = size\n        self.buckets = [[] for _ in range(size)]\n    def _hash(self, key):\n        return hash(key) % self.size\n    def put(self, key, value):\n        idx = self._hash(key)\n        for i, (k, v) in enumerate(self.buckets[idx]):\n            if k == key:\n                self.buckets[idx][i] = (key, value)\n                return\n        self.buckets[idx].append((key, value))\n    def get(self, key):\n        idx = self._hash(key)\n        for k, v in self.buckets[idx]:\n            if k == key:\n                return v\n        return None\n    def delete(self, key):\n        idx = self._hash(key)\n        self.buckets[idx] = [(k,v) for k,v in self.buckets[idx] if k != key]\n\nhm = HashMap(size=8)\nhm.put('name', 'Alice')\nhm.put('age', 25)\nhm.put('city', 'Sydney')\nprint(hm.get('name'))\nprint(hm.get('age'))\nhm.delete('age')\nprint(hm.get('age'))","Hash maps provide O(1) average-case lookup by converting keys to array indices. Chaining (using lists at each index) handles collisions when multiple keys hash to the same bucket.","SE: P6")
ex("Min Stack","Implement a stack that tracks the minimum element in O(1).","data_structures","stacks",5,"class MinStack:\n    # TODO: Implement push, pop, get_min all in O(1)\n    pass\n\ns = MinStack()\nfor v in [5, 3, 7, 1, 4]:\n    s.push(v)\nprint(s.get_min())\ns.pop()\ns.pop()\nprint(s.get_min())","1\n3","Keep a second stack that tracks minimums.","class MinStack:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.stack = []\n        self.min_stack = []\n    def push(self, val):\n        self.stack.append(val)\n        if not self.min_stack or val <= self.min_stack[-1]:\n            self.min_stack.append(val)\n    def pop(self):\n        val = self.stack.pop()\n        if val == self.min_stack[-1]:\n            self.min_stack.pop()\n        return val\n    def get_min(self):\n        return self.min_stack[-1]\n\ns = MinStack()\nfor v in [5, 3, 7, 1, 4]:\n    s.push(v)\nprint(s.get_min())\ns.pop()\ns.pop()\nprint(s.get_min())","The auxiliary min_stack stores the current minimum at each level. When we pop, we only pop from min_stack if the value equals the current minimum. This gives O(1) for all operations.","SE: P6")
ex("Trie (Prefix Tree)","Implement a Trie for word insertion and prefix searching.","data_structures","trees",6,"class Trie:\n    # TODO: Implement insert, search, starts_with\n    pass\n\nt = Trie()\nfor word in ['apple', 'app', 'application', 'banana']:\n    t.insert(word)\nprint(t.search('app'))\nprint(t.search('ap'))\nprint(t.starts_with('app'))","True\nFalse\nTrue","Each node stores children as a dict and a flag for word endings.","class TrieNode:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.children = {}\n        self.is_end = False\n\nclass Trie:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.root = TrieNode()\n    def insert(self, word):\n        node = self.root\n        for char in word:\n            if char not in node.children:\n                node.children[char] = TrieNode()\n            node = node.children[char]\n        node.is_end = True\n    def search(self, word):\n        node = self._find(word)\n        return node is not None and node.is_end\n    def starts_with(self, prefix):\n        return self._find(prefix) is not None\n    def _find(self, prefix):\n        node = self.root\n        for char in prefix:\n            if char not in node.children:\n                return None\n            node = node.children[char]\n        return node\n\nt = Trie()\nfor word in ['apple', 'app', 'application', 'banana']:\n    t.insert(word)\nprint(t.search('app'))\nprint(t.search('ap'))\nprint(t.starts_with('app'))","Tries are specialised trees for string storage. Each path from root to a node represents a prefix. They enable O(m) search where m is word length, regardless of dictionary size.","SE: P6")
ex("LRU Cache","Implement a Least Recently Used cache with O(1) get and put.","data_structures","hash_tables",7,"from collections import OrderedDict\n\nclass LRUCache:\n    # TODO: Implement with capacity limit\n    pass\n\ncache = LRUCache(3)\ncache.put('a', 1)\ncache.put('b', 2)\ncache.put('c', 3)\nprint(cache.get('a'))\ncache.put('d', 4)  # evicts 'b'\nprint(cache.get('b'))\nprint(cache.get('c'))","1\n-1\n3","OrderedDict maintains insertion order and supports move_to_end().","from collections import OrderedDict\n\nclass LRUCache:\n    def __init__(self, capacity):\n        self.cache = OrderedDict()\n        self.capacity = capacity\n    def get(self, key):\n        if key not in self.cache:\n            return -1\n        self.cache.move_to_end(key)\n        return self.cache[key]\n    def put(self, key, value):\n        if key in self.cache:\n            self.cache.move_to_end(key)\n        self.cache[key] = value\n        if len(self.cache) > self.capacity:\n            self.cache.popitem(last=False)\n\ncache = LRUCache(3)\ncache.put('a', 1)\ncache.put('b', 2)\ncache.put('c', 3)\nprint(cache.get('a'))\ncache.put('d', 4)\nprint(cache.get('b'))\nprint(cache.get('c'))","LRU Cache evicts the least recently used item when full. OrderedDict.move_to_end() marks items as recently used, and popitem(last=False) removes the oldest. This is how browser caches and database caches work.","SE: P6")

# === OOP (20 more) ===
ex("Class vs Static Methods","Demonstrate the difference between instance, class, and static methods.","oop","methods",3,"class Date:\n    # TODO: Implement with all three method types\n    pass\n\nd = Date(2026, 3, 17)\nprint(d)\nd2 = Date.from_string('2026-12-25')\nprint(d2)\nprint(Date.is_valid(2026, 2, 30))","2026-03-17\n2026-12-25\nFalse","@classmethod receives cls, @staticmethod receives neither self nor cls.","class Date:\n    def __init__(self, year, month, day):\n        self.year = year\n        self.month = month\n        self.day = day\n    def __repr__(self):\n        return f'{self.year:04d}-{self.month:02d}-{self.day:02d}'\n    @classmethod\n    def from_string(cls, date_str):\n        y, m, d = map(int, date_str.split('-'))\n        return cls(y, m, d)\n    @staticmethod\n    def is_valid(year, month, day):\n        if month < 1 or month > 12:\n            return False\n        days_in_month = [0,31,28,31,30,31,30,31,31,30,31,30,31]\n        return 1 <= day <= days_in_month[month]\n\nd = Date(2026, 3, 17)\nprint(d)\nd2 = Date.from_string('2026-12-25')\nprint(d2)\nprint(Date.is_valid(2026, 2, 30))","Instance methods access self, class methods access cls (useful for alternative constructors), and static methods are utility functions that belong to the class namespace but don't need class/instance access.","SE: P6")
ex("Composition over Inheritance","Use composition instead of inheritance for flexible design.","oop","design_patterns",5,"class Engine:\n    def __init__(self, hp):\n        self.hp = hp\n    def start(self):\n        return f'Engine ({self.hp}hp) started'\n\nclass GPS:\n    def navigate(self, dest):\n        return f'Navigating to {dest}'\n\n# TODO: Create Car using composition (has-a Engine and GPS)\n\ncar = Car('Tesla', Engine(300), GPS())\nprint(car.start())\nprint(car.navigate('Sydney'))","Engine (300hp) started\nNavigating to Sydney","Store components as instance variables and delegate method calls.","class Engine:\n    def __init__(self, hp):\n        self.hp = hp\n    def start(self):\n        return f'Engine ({self.hp}hp) started'\n\nclass GPS:\n    def navigate(self, dest):\n        return f'Navigating to {dest}'\n\nclass Car:\n    def __init__(self, name, engine, gps):\n        self.name = name\n        self.engine = engine\n        self.gps = gps\n    def start(self):\n        return self.engine.start()\n    def navigate(self, dest):\n        return self.gps.navigate(dest)\n\ncar = Car('Tesla', Engine(300), GPS())\nprint(car.start())\nprint(car.navigate('Sydney'))","Composition (has-a) is more flexible than inheritance (is-a). You can swap components at runtime, combine capabilities freely, and avoid deep inheritance hierarchies.","SE: P6")
ex("Observer Pattern","Implement the Observer pattern for event-driven communication.","oop","design_patterns",6,"class EventEmitter:\n    # TODO: Implement on(), off(), emit()\n    pass\n\nemitter = EventEmitter()\ndef on_data(data):\n    print(f'Received: {data}')\ndef on_log(data):\n    print(f'Log: {data}')\n\nemitter.on('data', on_data)\nemitter.on('data', on_log)\nemitter.emit('data', 'Hello!')\nemitter.off('data', on_log)\nemitter.emit('data', 'World!')","Received: Hello!\nLog: Hello!\nReceived: World!","Use a dict mapping event names to lists of callback functions.","class EventEmitter:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._listeners = {}\n    def on(self, event, callback):\n        if event not in self._listeners:\n            self._listeners[event] = []\n        self._listeners[event].append(callback)\n    def off(self, event, callback):\n        if event in self._listeners:\n            self._listeners[event].remove(callback)\n    def emit(self, event, *args):\n        for callback in self._listeners.get(event, []):\n            callback(*args)\n\nemitter = EventEmitter()\ndef on_data(data):\n    print(f'Received: {data}')\ndef on_log(data):\n    print(f'Log: {data}')\n\nemitter.on('data', on_data)\nemitter.on('data', on_log)\nemitter.emit('data', 'Hello!')\nemitter.off('data', on_log)\nemitter.emit('data', 'World!')","The Observer pattern decouples event producers from consumers. This is the foundation of event-driven architectures, GUI frameworks, and reactive programming.","SE: P6")
ex("Iterator Protocol","Implement the iterator protocol for a custom range-like class.","oop","dunder_methods",4,"class CountDown:\n    # TODO: Implement __iter__ and __next__\n    pass\n\nfor n in CountDown(5):\n    print(n, end=' ')\nprint()","5 4 3 2 1 ","__iter__ returns self, __next__ returns next value or raises StopIteration.","class CountDown:\n    def __init__(self, start):\n        self.current = start\n    def __iter__(self):\n        return self\n    def __next__(self):\n        if self.current <= 0:\n            raise StopIteration\n        val = self.current\n        self.current -= 1\n        return val\n\nfor n in CountDown(5):\n    print(n, end=' ')\nprint()","The iterator protocol requires __iter__ (return the iterator) and __next__ (return next value or raise StopIteration). This enables any object to work in for loops, comprehensions, and unpacking.","SE: P6")
ex("Slots for Memory Efficiency","Use __slots__ to reduce memory usage in classes with many instances.","oop","optimisation",5,"import sys\n\nclass PointRegular:\n    def __init__(self, x, y):\n        self.x = x\n        self.y = y\n\nclass PointSlots:\n    __slots__ = ['x', 'y']\n    def __init__(self, x, y):\n        self.x = x\n        self.y = y\n\nr = PointRegular(1, 2)\ns = PointSlots(1, 2)\nprint(f'Regular size: {sys.getsizeof(r.__dict__)} bytes (has __dict__)')\nprint(f'Slots: no __dict__ (more memory efficient)')\nprint(f'Values equal: {r.x == s.x and r.y == s.y}')","Regular size: 64 bytes (has __dict__)\nSlots: no __dict__ (more memory efficient)\nValues equal: True","__slots__ prevents __dict__ creation, saving ~50 bytes per instance.","import sys\n\nclass PointRegular:\n    def __init__(self, x, y):\n        self.x = x\n        self.y = y\n\nclass PointSlots:\n    __slots__ = ['x', 'y']\n    def __init__(self, x, y):\n        self.x = x\n        self.y = y\n\nr = PointRegular(1, 2)\ns = PointSlots(1, 2)\nprint(f'Regular size: {sys.getsizeof(r.__dict__)} bytes (has __dict__)')\nprint(f'Slots: no __dict__ (more memory efficient)')\nprint(f'Values equal: {r.x == s.x and r.y == s.y}')","__slots__ eliminates the per-instance __dict__, saving memory when creating millions of objects. The trade-off: you can't add attributes not listed in __slots__.","SE: P6")

