ex("Quick Sort","Implement quicksort with a pivot selection strategy.","algorithms","sorting",4,"def quicksort(arr):\n    # TODO: Implement quicksort\n    pass\n\nprint(quicksort([3, 6, 8, 10, 1, 2, 1]))","[1, 1, 2, 3, 6, 8, 10]","Choose a pivot, partition into less/equal/greater, recurse.","def quicksort(arr):\n    if len(arr) <= 1:\n        return arr\n    pivot = arr[len(arr) // 2]\n    left = [x for x in arr if x < pivot]\n    middle = [x for x in arr if x == pivot]\n    right = [x for x in arr if x > pivot]\n    return quicksort(left) + middle + quicksort(right)\n\nprint(quicksort([3, 6, 8, 10, 1, 2, 1]))","This Lomuto-style quicksort is clean but uses extra space. Average O(n log n), worst case O(n²) with bad pivots. The middle partition handles duplicates efficiently.","SE: P3")
ex("DFS Graph Traversal","Implement depth-first search for graph traversal.","algorithms","graph_algorithms",4,"def dfs(graph, start):\n    # TODO: Return DFS traversal order\n    pass\n\ngraph = {'A':['B','C'],'B':['A','D'],'C':['A','E'],'D':['B'],'E':['C','F'],'F':['E']}\nprint(dfs(graph, 'A'))","['A', 'B', 'D', 'C', 'E', 'F']","Use a stack (or recursion) and a visited set.","def dfs(graph, start):\n    visited = []\n    stack = [start]\n    seen = set()\n    while stack:\n        node = stack.pop()\n        if node not in seen:\n            seen.add(node)\n            visited.append(node)\n            for neighbour in reversed(graph[node]):\n                if neighbour not in seen:\n                    stack.append(neighbour)\n    return visited\n\ngraph = {'A':['B','C'],'B':['A','D'],'C':['A','E'],'D':['B'],'E':['C','F'],'F':['E']}\nprint(dfs(graph, 'A'))","DFS explores as deep as possible before backtracking. Using a stack gives iterative DFS. Reversing neighbours ensures left-to-right traversal matching the adjacency list order.","SE: P3")
ex("Two Sum Problem","Find two numbers in an array that add up to a target.","algorithms","searching",2,"def two_sum(nums, target):\n    # TODO: Return indices of the two numbers\n    pass\n\nprint(two_sum([2, 7, 11, 15], 9))\nprint(two_sum([3, 2, 4], 6))","[0, 1]\n[1, 2]","Use a hash map to store complements.","def two_sum(nums, target):\n    seen = {}\n    for i, n in enumerate(nums):\n        complement = target - n\n        if complement in seen:\n            return [seen[complement], i]\n        seen[n] = i\n    return []\n\nprint(two_sum([2, 7, 11, 15], 9))\nprint(two_sum([3, 2, 4], 6))","The hash map approach is O(n) vs O(n²) for brute force. For each number, we check if its complement (target - num) was seen before. This is one of the most common interview questions.","SE: P3")
ex("Insertion Sort","Implement insertion sort, optimal for small or nearly-sorted arrays.","algorithms","sorting",2,"def insertion_sort(arr):\n    # TODO: Implement insertion sort\n    pass\n\nnums = [12, 11, 13, 5, 6]\ninsertion_sort(nums)\nprint(nums)","[5, 6, 11, 12, 13]","Take each element and insert it into its correct position in the sorted portion.","def insertion_sort(arr):\n    for i in range(1, len(arr)):\n        key = arr[i]\n        j = i - 1\n        while j >= 0 and arr[j] > key:\n            arr[j + 1] = arr[j]\n            j -= 1\n        arr[j + 1] = key\n\nnums = [12, 11, 13, 5, 6]\ninsertion_sort(nums)\nprint(nums)","Insertion sort is O(n²) worst case but O(n) for nearly-sorted data. It's stable, in-place, and often used for small subarrays within merge sort or quicksort.","SE: P3")
ex("Knapsack Problem","Solve the 0/1 knapsack problem using dynamic programming.","algorithms","dynamic_programming",6,"def knapsack(capacity, weights, values):\n    # TODO: Find maximum value that fits in capacity\n    pass\n\nweights = [2, 3, 4, 5]\nvalues = [3, 4, 5, 6]\nprint(knapsack(5, weights, values))","7","Build a 2D table: dp[i][w] = max value using first i items with capacity w.","def knapsack(capacity, weights, values):\n    n = len(weights)\n    dp = [[0] * (capacity + 1) for _ in range(n + 1)]\n    for i in range(1, n + 1):\n        for w in range(capacity + 1):\n            dp[i][w] = dp[i-1][w]\n            if weights[i-1] <= w:\n                dp[i][w] = max(dp[i][w], dp[i-1][w-weights[i-1]] + values[i-1])\n    return dp[n][capacity]\n\nweights = [2, 3, 4, 5]\nvalues = [3, 4, 5, 6]\nprint(knapsack(5, weights, values))","The 0/1 knapsack is a classic DP problem. Each item is either taken or not. The 2D table builds solutions bottom-up, considering each item at each capacity level. Time: O(n*W), Space: O(n*W).","SE: P3")
ex("Longest Common Subsequence","Find the length of the longest common subsequence of two strings.","algorithms","dynamic_programming",5,"def lcs(s1, s2):\n    # TODO: Find LCS length\n    pass\n\nprint(lcs('ABCBDAB', 'BDCAB'))","4","Build a 2D table comparing characters from both strings.","def lcs(s1, s2):\n    m, n = len(s1), len(s2)\n    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]\n    for i in range(1, m + 1):\n        for j in range(1, n + 1):\n            if s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]:\n                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1\n            else:\n                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])\n    return dp[m][n]\n\nprint(lcs('ABCBDAB', 'BDCAB'))","LCS is foundational for diff algorithms (like git diff). When characters match, extend the diagonal. Otherwise, take the max of excluding either character. Time: O(mn).","SE: P3")

# === FILE HANDLING (15 more) ===
ex("File Copy with Progress","Copy a file showing progress percentage.","file_handling","binary_files",3,"import os\n\n# TODO: Copy file with progress reporting\n","Copying... 33%\nCopying... 67%\nCopying... 100%\nDone! Copied 300 bytes","Read and write in chunks, tracking bytes copied.","import os\n\n# Create sample file\nwith open('source.bin', 'wb') as f:\n    f.write(b'x' * 300)\n\ndef copy_with_progress(src, dst, chunk_size=100):\n    total = os.path.getsize(src)\n    copied = 0\n    with open(src, 'rb') as fin, open(dst, 'wb') as fout:\n        while True:\n            chunk = fin.read(chunk_size)\n            if not chunk:\n                break\n            fout.write(chunk)\n            copied += len(chunk)\n            pct = int(copied / total * 100)\n            print(f'Copying... {pct}%')\n    print(f'Done! Copied {copied} bytes')\n\ncopy_with_progress('source.bin', 'dest.bin')\nos.remove('source.bin')\nos.remove('dest.bin')","Chunk-based copying handles files of any size without loading everything into memory. Binary mode ('rb'/'wb') is essential for non-text files.","SE: P6")
ex("Pathlib Operations","Use pathlib for modern file path handling.","file_handling","pathlib",2,"from pathlib import Path\n\n# TODO: Show pathlib operations\n","Home: exists\nCurrent: exists\nSuffix of test.py: .py\nStem of test.py: test","pathlib provides an object-oriented interface to filesystem paths.","from pathlib import Path\n\nhome = Path.home()\nprint(f'Home: {\"exists\" if home.exists() else \"missing\"}')\n\ncwd = Path.cwd()\nprint(f'Current: {\"exists\" if cwd.exists() else \"missing\"}')\n\np = Path('test.py')\nprint(f'Suffix of {p}: {p.suffix}')\nprint(f'Stem of {p}: {p.stem}')","pathlib (Python 3.4+) replaces os.path with an OOP interface. Path objects support / operator for joining, .suffix for extension, .stem for filename without extension.","SE: P6")
ex("YAML Config Reader","Read and write YAML configuration files.","file_handling","config_files",3,"import json, os\n\n# TODO: Read/write config in a structured format (using JSON as YAML-like)\n","Config: {'database': {'host': 'localhost', 'port': 5432}, 'debug': True}","Use json as a stand-in for structured config (YAML requires pyyaml).","import json, os\n\nconfig = {'database': {'host': 'localhost', 'port': 5432}, 'debug': True}\n\nwith open('config.json', 'w') as f:\n    json.dump(config, f, indent=2)\n\nwith open('config.json', 'r') as f:\n    loaded = json.load(f)\n    print(f'Config: {loaded}')\n\nos.remove('config.json')","Structured config files (JSON, YAML, TOML) are better than plain text for nested settings. JSON is built-in; YAML requires pyyaml; TOML is built-in from Python 3.11.","SE: P6")
ex("Temporary Files","Use tempfile for safe temporary file creation.","file_handling","temp_files",3,"import tempfile\nimport os\n\n# TODO: Create and use temporary files safely\n","Temp file created and cleaned up automatically","tempfile handles creation and cleanup of temp files.","import tempfile\nimport os\n\nwith tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(mode='w', suffix='.txt', delete=False) as f:\n    f.write('Temporary data')\n    temp_path = f.name\n\nwith open(temp_path, 'r') as f:\n    content = f.read()\n\nos.unlink(temp_path)\nprint('Temp file created and cleaned up automatically')","tempfile creates files in the OS temp directory with unique names. NamedTemporaryFile gives you a path you can reopen. delete=False keeps the file after closing for manual cleanup.","SE: P6")

